Alex Wasik, an incoming 10th grader at CHS, spent his summer making 500 masks that he is donating to the school district. Today, he delivered the masks to our superintendent, Steve King. This is part of his work to earn his Eagle Scout Badge which he hopes to earn by the end of this year. These are masks with cool designs and are made in multiple sizes so that students of all grade levels can use them. Thanks Alex for helping our schools and community stay safe! #coupevillestrong

post_text:
Coupeville Middle School would like to take a moment to welcome the graduating class of 2027 to CMS!

On Tuesday, June 2, Ms. Yoder, Ms. Beck, and Mr. Kappes gave a big welcome to all incoming sixth graders with a visit to their homes! They gave each student a CMS t-shirt, a CMS Transition Handbook, and a yard sign identifying their house as a home of a new middle school student! The students were excited to see the CMS staff stop by but our CMS team was even more excited to meet their new students!

Parents of 5th grade students please stay tuned for emails and details about orientation in late August. Please be flexible with us - all events will be dependent on OSPI/Island County guidelines.

Welcome to Coupeville Middle School!

As most of you know we had a school board meeting this past Monday night where we tried to live stream the meeting so our entire community could be in virtual attendance. Unfortunately, some of our community members were not able to stream the meeting on Monday because of tech issues. Our school board meeting had some critical issues that the board needs to take action on and we feel it is important that no one is excluded from these decisions our district is making and the information that is driving these decisions. Therefore, we are going to hold another school board meeting on Monday where our ‚ÄúNew Business‚Äù items will be reconsidered by the board. Please see our attached agenda with instructions on how to access our meeting.

Thank you,

Steve King

post_text: Our Coupeville team has been working hard during this school closure to continue to show that we love each and every child. This has been a team effort to continue to provide daily lunches for our students. We are now sending instructional materials to students who need them on our buses with our lunch deliveries. Our tech department is preparing extra chromebooks for families who need devices for distance learning. Our staff and students enjoy connecting at the bus stops giving us hope that hopefully someday soon things will return to normal for everyone. Our students are now learning from home and our teaching staff is adapting all of their instruction to an online and distance learning model. We are proud of the way our staff, community, and families have come together to continue to love and support our students and families during this time. Go Wolves! #hope #coupeville #coupevillestrong #community

Dear Coupeville Families,

Per Governor Jay Inslee‚Äôs executive order, Coupeville Schools will join the rest of the school districts in Washington State to close schools beginning Tuesday, March 17, through April 24. At this time, the earliest students will be back in our schools will be Monday, April 27. Schools will be open Monday, March 16, for students to collect their belongings, receive instructional materials and gather any essential education items necessary for the extended closure.

Steve King, Superintendent Coupeville Schools

post_text:
You might consider a Chef, a Farmer, and a Superintendent sort of an odd combination. But in Coupeville they are a team that has been the foundation of our Connected Food Program.
Tonight this team held another successful Community Dinner, connecting nearly 300 community members, with all donations going directly to support scratch cooking with whole foods, and to help us with local sourcing. Kyle & Paige, from @bells_strawberry_farm arm were there to talk about their farm and share about the amazing benefits of regenerative farming. The Shepherd‚Äôs Pie was made with ingredients from Bell‚Äôs Farm and the Blueberry Compote with blueberries from @mutinybayblues .
We also had students on hand to have community members sign a letter to the Town declaring a state of emergency in regards to climate change. We are proud of our students advocating for our environment.
We would like to thank our amazing Connected Food staff and our local partners, and to give a special thanks to our custodial staff. #community #whidbeyisland #whidbeyislandgrown #wholefoods #food #coupeville #school

You still have time to sign up for our next Community Dinner on Thursday, February 27, 2020 from 5:30-6:30 p.m.

The dinner will take place in the CHS Commons and we will have the owners of @bells_strawberry_farm present to share information about their farm, including their work with regenerative farming.

This meal represents how much we care for our students each school day and demonstrates our goals of scratch cooking with whole foods and local sourcing. We look forward to seeing you there!

post_text:
Rick Larsen, Congressman representing Washington's 2nd district, visited Coupeville today and met with our Superintendent Steve King. Mr. King was able to share and discuss the following topics with the Congressman.
1. The need for increased funding for Special Education and Title Programs.
2. Impact Aid from the federal government to assist with military families in Coupeville.
3. Collaboration between our communities Coupeville Farm To School program and our School District Connected Food program leading to great school lunches for our students. Mr. Larsen has been invited to our next community dinner!
4. The problems with the National School Lunch Program and how they create barriers for providing healthy meals to our students.
5. Jet noise in Coupeville and the impact on schools.

Thank you to Congressman Larsen for coming to Coupeville to support us and see how you can support our schools!

post_text:
In honor of Veterans Day, Coupeville Schools held assemblies thanking our Military community for their service. Many of our staff, parents and community veterans attended these events. NASWI had one of their Search & Rescue helicopters scheduled to do a demonstration and be the guest speakers at our assembly. Unfortunately, due to our Whidbey Island fog, they were unable to land. Our Middle and High School assembly discussed the Star Spangled Banner, the history of Veterans Day, our Band played The Armed Forces on Parade, and we watched videos provided by NASWI Search and Rescue. At the Coupeville Elementary School assembly, our Boy Scouts presented Colors and both our Boy and Girls Scouts said theirs oaths. Students and Military members spoke about Veterans Day, a video was presented with our students and their Military family members and TAPS was played on the trumpet to close the assembly.

We thank all of our Veterans and their families and are so proud of what they do for us and our Nation. Thank you Veterans and GO Wolves!!

Marenna‚Äôs essay was one of the top six in the entire state and therefore she was chosen to receive this year's Dave ‚ÄúHendu‚Äù Henderson Education Scholarship. Tonight the Connected Food Program had its first Community dinner. This took place in our cafeteria on our secondary campus before our homecoming football game. We served one of the meals that has been served to our students. We had an unbelievable amount of participation from our Community with over 400 people attending. We are very appreciative of the support the Coupeville Community provides to our students and schools. All of tonight's donations went directly to support scratch cooking, whole foods, and local sourcing. We would like to thank our amazing Food Service Staff for everything they do everyday for our students and for making this event such a success. Thank you to our local farms and community for your continued support and dedication to Coupeville Schools, Students and Staff.

Special thanks to our custodial staff for the extra efforts with set up and clean up. Such a great team of staff members!

Thank you Coupeville and Go Wolves!!

So great to have our students back with us today. The day was highlighted by our community greeters welcoming our students and families back to school and also the first day our our Connected Food Program.
Our community greeters included Lions Club, Community Foundation For Coupeville Public Schools, School Board, Coupeville Mayor & Marshall, and members of the Navy. Each student was given a red pencil as they arrived that said, ‚ÄúCoupeville Loves Their Kids.‚Äù
Today our new food service team served 389 lunches compared to serving 191 on the first day of school last year. Students were excited about the food and that our schools are now using real plates and silverware and have eliminated paper and plastic.
We are so thankful for our community that partners with our staff to show such great care for our students. Go Wolves!

post_text:
With the goal of creating a food service program that connects to our community's values we are excited to share information on the program that we will launch next week. Thanks to the work of our new team and input from our students and community, we have September menus and our new Connected Food Guide that was created by a committee that includes students, staff, parents, and community members. This program has been built with the foundations of scratch based cooking with whole foods and local sourcing. We have done all of this without increasing the prices of our lunches for our students. If you would like to get your students account started so they can take advantage of this new program, you can do so at your school office or online at EFunds. We now accept debit and credit card payments at the schools to make things more convenient for our families.
Soon we will be announcing community dinners to involve our community and increase funding.
Also, you can follow our new program more closely by following our new Connected Food Facebook page @CoupevilleConnectedFoodProgram

post_text:
Did you know you had a CHOICE?
If you would like to attend Coupeville Schools, but you are in a different school district, you have the CHOICE to attend Coupeville. Coupeville schools have many great advantages including small class sizes. Also, because we are a small school district with a very caring staff, our students develop great connections with other students, staff, and our supportive and involved community.
If you are interested, the process is easy: 1. Fill out the CHOICE Transfer Form or go online to the Choice Transfer Request Portal (CTRP); 2. Call the school of your CHOICE and start the registration process. Coupeville Elementary (360) 678-2474, Coupeville Middle or Coupeville High (360) 678-2415, Coupeville Open Den (360) 678-2472. Forms and access to the CTRP are located at http://www.coupeville.k12.wa.us/schools/forms

As the end of the 2019 School year quickly approaches, we would like to say thank you to all of our Teachers, Staff, FireFighters and community volunteers for putting on an AWESOME Coupeville Elementary Field Day. Coupeville Schools
April 26, 2019 at 2:23 PM ¬∑

King 5 News came to the little town of Coupeville today to find out about the "Connected Food" program we are launching for our students in September. For the interviews, they spoke with our new food services director Andreas Wurzrainer and our superintendent Steven King. In the interviews they discussed the community connection that we want to have in our food service program and our close partnership with groups like Coupeville Farm-to-School. They also discussed the positive impact they want to have on students. They are planning to have the story on King 5 News tonight beginning with the 4:00 pm broadcast. If you miss the story live we will post the story on our FB page over the weekend.

Thank you to our community and to our Coupeville Farm-to-School program for your great support and input that helped us start this program. We look forward to our continued collaboration and connection with community, staff, and students as we build this program.

shared_text:
Coupeville Schools
April 23, 2019 at 4:12 PM ¬∑

At our School Board meeting on Monday some of our Transition students and their teacher, Melissa Casey, came and presented to the board and the public. Our Transition Program is for special education students who are 18-21 years old and are learning job skills to prepare them for life as adults. The students did most of the talking as they explained many of the things they do during the day to help other students and staff. These students are also learning job skills for future employment. We then honored them for their hard work on campus by giving them certificates from the School Board.

We were so thankful to have our students with us at the meeting and for all they do. They are connected with the rest of the students and staff in the schools and they are an important part of our school district. We also appreciate the work and dedication of Mrs. Casey as she does a great job with these young adults.

Thanks to the parents and community members who attended to help honor them.

Last night our Coupeville School Board honored Danny Conlisk who served as our student School Board Member for 2018. Having a student representative is very important as we want to hear from our students as we make decisions regarding our school district. Danny did a fantastic job of not only representing the High School but also representing all schools in the district. You will see some of the staff members that played a role in Danny's life here in Coupeville Schools. For the next calendar year our School Board has selected 11th grader, Christiane (Tia) Wurzrainer and we look forward to working with her.

Coupeville Schools
December 14, 2018 at 2:37 PM ¬∑

On Saturday December 8th, our Elementary and Middle School Robotics teams competed in the First Lego League event in Mount Vernon. We are thankful for our Coupeville Education Foundation for supporting this event by paying for the entry and registration fees. We are also thankful for our community support through the levy which funds enrichment programs like this. This is all part of our Science, Technology, Engineering, Art, & Math (STEAM) initiative to provide hands on and activity based learning experiences for our students.

We are so thankful for our students, staff, and great community support. Go Wolves!

shared_text:
Coupeville Schools
November 28, 2018 at 3:05 PM ¬∑

At our November 26 school board meeting Mr. Noste, our Coupeville Elementary School robotics teacher, recognized some of our fantastic 5th grade students who are giving up their lunch recess time to help younger students in robotics. These students are: Chase Anderson, Teagan Calkins, Caroline Eckardt, Kiefer Mead, Jeann Nitta, Heidi Schroeder, Frankie Tenore, Merrill Walther, Noelle Western, and Adrian Cunningham.
Mr. Noste, and principal Dave Ebersole, also highlighted some of the projects our students are doing in our robotics program. This is a program for all of our elementary students K-5 and provides hands on or applied learning opportunities for students. It is a great example of our districts work to incorporate more STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Art, & Math) into our student school day. This program is only possible because of our community support as it is a levy funded activity that our voters approved. Thank you to Mr. Noste, to our wonderful leadership students, and to our community for your support.

Coupeville Schools is with Michelle Glass.
November 9, 2018 at 4:03 PM ¬∑

Today, with the help of students, staff, active duty service members, and Veterans, we had the privilege of celebrating Veterans Day in each of our schools. As a district, we are so thankful for our Veterans and our active duty service members. We are also grateful for the family members in military families as they make many sacrifices as well. In Coupeville it is an honor to serve those who serve us! To all Veterans and military families we say thank you!

Here are a few pictures of some of our assemblies.

October 5, 2018 at 8:35 AM ¬∑

This week we celebrated Taste Washington Day, an annual celebration of Washington grown foods, by providing our students with fresh with organic produce from our school garden. We are so thankful for our Coupeville Farm to School program which teaches our students about the health benefits of eating local, organic, fruits and vegetables. Whether it is in the classroom or in the cafeteria our kids deserve the very best! Go Wolves!
